# Pathfinder2e Class Descriptions
Alchemist — The mad scientist of the party. Alchemists use a daily pool of Infused Reagents to produce powerful bombs, healing elixirs, mutagens, and poisons for free. Their research field shapes whether they lean into blowing things up, buffing themselves into a superhuman, or poisoning enemies and healing allies on the cheap.
Animist — A divine spellcaster who channels the power of spirits called Apparitions that inhabit the natural world. Uniquely, Animists are both prepared and spontaneous casters simultaneously, shifting which spirits they commune with daily and gaining different spells and abilities depending on the Apparitions they invoke. They're flexible, nature-flavored divine casters with a strong ritualistic identity.
Barbarian — Pure front-line fury. Barbarians enter a supernatural Rage that boosts their damage, toughness, and grants special abilities, at the cost of not being able to focus on precise tasks. Their Instinct (animal, dragon, giant, etc.) determines the flavor and nature of their rage, making each barbarian feel distinct while all sharing the same "hit things very hard" core identity.
Bard — The consummate support caster and social operator. Bards use occult magic and Performance-based Compositions to buff allies, debuff enemies, and control the battlefield. Their Muse shapes their specialization, and while they're capable in combat, they truly shine in social encounters and any situation where flexibility and cleverness win the day.
Champion — The divine warrior and protector, PF2e's answer to the paladin. Champions are heavily armored melee combatants who channel their deity's power into defensive reactions and holy/unholy attacks. Their Cause (Paladin, Liberator, Redeemer, etc.) determines whether they focus on protecting allies, punishing enemies, or something in between — all with a strong roleplaying identity tied to their deity.
Cleric — The definitive divine caster. Clerics draw power from their deity and choose between two doctrines: Cloistered (pure spellcaster focused on spell slots and versatility) or Warpriest (armored battle-cleric who can swing weapons effectively). They're the gold standard for healing and divine magic, with enormous flexibility through their spell list and the divine font ability.
Druid — A primal spellcaster deeply tied to nature. Druids pick an Order that shapes their focus — Wild druids wild-shape into animals, Leaf druids support and heal, Storm druids blast with weather magic, Animal druids bond with a companion, etc. They're versatile and powerful, covering everything from blasting to tanking to summoning depending on how they're built.
Exemplar — A warrior touched by divinity, reforging the boundary between mortal and god. Exemplars channel divine power through Ikons — sacred objects, body features, or weapons — that can be activated in two distinct modes. They're a highly mobile, high-impact martial class that plays with a unique push-pull of empowering your Ikon vs. reclaiming that spark for other benefits.
Fighter — The absolute master of martial combat. Fighters have the highest attack progression in the game, access to the widest variety of weapons, and more combat feats than anyone. They don't have any magic or special resources — just superior training, precision, and the ability to do absolutely devastating things with a weapon. Simple in concept, deep in execution.
Gunslinger — The firearms and crossbow specialist. Gunslingers pick a Way (like Drifter or Pistolero) that defines their combat style, and their core mechanic revolves around gaining and spending Grit Points for powerful deeds. They fill a similar niche to the Fighter but with a unique flavor around readying, reloading, and exploiting enemy positions with ranged weaponry.
Guardian — A purpose-built tank whose entire design revolves around drawing attacks and protecting allies. Guardians have exceptional AC, hit points, and a suite of reactions and abilities that make enemies want to hit them instead of their friends. They're the most explicitly defensive class in the game, made for players who want their character to be the living wall between danger and the party.
Inventor — A tinkerer who builds and bonds with a custom invention — a weapon, armor, or construct companion — that they continuously upgrade and modify. The Inventor's Overdrive ability lets them push their creation to dangerous extremes, and they have a unique "unstable" mechanic where big effects carry a risk of malfunction. Great for players who love the "mad engineer" fantasy.
Investigator — The INT-based martial who wins fights by thinking. Investigators use Devise a Stratagem to pre-calculate their attack roll using INT before striking, turning combat into a puzzle to be solved. They get more skill increases than almost any other class, excel at out-of-combat investigation and knowledge gathering, and have a strong ongoing Case system for investigation-focused play.
Kineticist — The elemental channeler who never runs out of juice. Kineticists choose one or more elements and shape them through Impulses — abilities that work like spells but require no spell slots or focus points, just Overflow management. They can range from durable frontliners (earth) to sustained ranged blasters (fire, air) to healers (water), and their unlimited-use core identity makes them uniquely consistent.
Magus — The arcane warrior who fuses spellcasting with melee combat. The Magus's signature ability, Spellstrike, lets them channel a spell through a weapon attack, delivering both at once. Their Hybrid Study determines their unique combat approach, and they're all about charging up Spellstrike, delivering it for massive combined damage, and then working to recharge it again.
Monk — The unarmored martial arts master. Monks fight without weapons or armor, using their body and a rich system of Stances and Strikes (including unarmed attacks that scale in damage with level) to devastating effect. They also have access to Ki spells — focus spells powered by inner discipline — and are one of the most versatile and distinct-feeling martial classes.
Oracle — The cursed divine spontaneous caster. Oracles gain powerful divine magic from a Mystery (bone, flames, battle, etc.) but are burdened by a Curse that intensifies the more they use their power. Playing an Oracle is a constant push-and-pull of embracing your curse for greater power while managing its escalating drawbacks — a high-risk, high-reward caster identity.
Psychic — An occult spontaneous caster who wields mental and psychic power. Psychics use an Unleash Psyche mode for burst moments of amplified magical output, with their Conscious Mind determining their spell and ability flavor. They play with a dual-resource system and emphasize cantrips more than most casters, since their amplified cantrips can become devastatingly powerful.
Ranger — The wilderness expert and precision striker. Rangers track, hunt, and eliminate targets using Hunt Prey to gain bonuses against a designated quarry. They can specialize in archery, two-weapon fighting, or animal companions, and have strong out-of-combat utility through Survival and tracking. They're martial through and through, with optional primal spellcasting via a feat.
Rogue — The ultimate skill monkey and Sneak Attack specialist. Rogues get the most skills in the game, can make almost any skill legendary, and deal significant bonus damage against enemies who are off-guard. Their Racket determines their flavor and fighting style, and they're the class for players who want to be good at everything, sneaky, tricky, and surprisingly dangerous.
Sorcerer — The spontaneous arcane/divine/primal/occult caster with more raw spell slots than anyone. Sorcerers draw magic from a Bloodline that determines their tradition and bonus spells, and while they know fewer spells than a wizard, they can cast the ones they know far more times per day. They're all about raw magical output and leaning into whatever flavor their bloodline provides.
Summoner — The ultimate pet class. Summoners bond with a customizable magical creature called an Eidolon, and the two share a pool of actions and HP in a deeply intertwined way. You build your Eidolon like a secondary character, choosing its form and abilities as you level. The class is all about fighting as a unified duo — you and your creature as a single, terrifying team.
Swashbuckler — The stylish duelist who builds Panache through daring feats and spends it on powerful Finishers. Swashbucklers are DEX-based melee fighters who thrive on momentum and flair, rewarded for taking risks, making theatrical moves, and finishing combos with high-impact flourishes. They're strong in one-on-one fights and have better social skills than most martial classes.
Witch — A spellcaster who gains power from a Patron, a mysterious entity that grants a familiar and determines their magical tradition. The Witch's familiar delivers their spells and lessons (focus spells unique to their Patron), and the class has a strong "curse and debuff your enemies" identity alongside flexible tradition-based spellcasting. They're versatile, slightly sinister, and deeply familiar-dependent.
Wizard — The ultimate prepared arcane spellcaster. Wizards prepare spells from a massive spellbook each day and gain a Thesis that defines their unique magical approach. They know far more spells than any other class, can adapt their daily preparation to whatever the situation demands, and their School of Magic determines their bonus spells and arcane thesis. The definitive "master of magic through study" class.
